ntsync 1015: dedicated kmem_cache for the per-ioctl wait queue (struct ntsync_q)

Audit of post1014a (srcversion F1A9EA24E257A35BB21341D) found exactly one
HOT remaining kmalloc class in ntsync.c after 1013 absorbed event_pi /
channel_entry / pi_owner: the per-ioctl wait queue allocated by setup_wait
and ntsync_aggregate_setup at the WAIT_ANY / WAIT_ALL / AGGREGATE_WAIT
entry points.

Site enumeration (post1014a line numbers — source-of-truth snapshot is
ntsync.c.post1014):

    1974  ntsync_thread_reg     per channel thread-register   COLD  - skip
    2160  ntsync_obj            per CreateEvent/Mutex/Sem     COOL  - marginal
  **2383  wait queue q          per WAIT_ANY/WAIT_ALL ioctl   HOT   - target**
  **2829  wait queue q (agg)    per AGGREGATE_WAIT ioctl      HOT   - target**
    2840  fds array             per wait-with-FDs (var-count) -     - not eligible
    3092  ntsync_device         per chardev open              COLD  - skip

Only the two wait-queue allocations are on the audio dispatcher hot path.
Every block-completion fires WAIT_* ioctls from AudioCalc workers + MidiOut
+ MainThread; each pays a kmalloc-N traversal and shares a cacheline class
with arbitrary system callers.

Why a dedicated cache extends the same lever as 1013
====================================================

Same four arguments that motivated 1013, applied to the only remaining
HOT kmalloc class:

  1. Cacheline isolation.  SLAB_HWCACHE_ALIGN puts each slot on its own
     cacheline boundary; no false sharing between concurrent waits on
     different CPUs.

  2. Per-cpu freelist locality.  AudioCalc workers + MidiOut + MainThread
     all cycle through this allocator constantly; SLUB's per-cpu freelist
     keeps recently-freed slots warm for the next allocation, instead of
     intermixing with arbitrary system traffic in kmalloc-N.

  3. Isolation from kmalloc-N callers.  Pre-1015, ntsync_q allocations
     for ~72-352B share kmalloc-128 / kmalloc-256 / kmalloc-512 with
     network buffers, fs metadata, and any other 100-300B caller.
     Coherence traffic from those neighbors hits us as RT jitter.

  4. /proc/slabinfo + /sys/kernel/slab/ntsync_wait_q visibility.  Per-
     cache object counts, partial-slab usage, cpu_slabs activity all
     directly observable for future tuning.

Variable-size design
====================

struct ntsync_q has a flexible-array member; the alloc size is
struct_size(q, entries, total_count) where total_count ranges from 1
(typical audio worker) up to NTSYNC_MAX_WAIT_COUNT+1 = 65 (cap on
NtWaitForMultipleObjects) or NTSYNC_AGG_MAX = 64 (aggregate wait).

Three options were considered (in order of simplicity):

  (a) Single fixed-size cache for "up to 16 entries"; kmalloc fallback
      for total_count > 16.  Cleanest.

  (b) Two-tier: small (≤16) + large (≤64) caches; kmalloc above.
      Halves typical-case per-slot waste but doubles cache count.

  (c) Per-cpu pre-allocated buffer pool with sized slots.  More code,
      marginal extra win.

Shipping (a).  16 entries comfortably covers the typical 1-8 audio wait
depth; larger waits (rare) keep the existing kmalloc path with no
regression.  Slot size with SLAB_HWCACHE_ALIGN ≈ 704B on x86_64 (64B
cacheline rounding of header(32) + 16*entry(40) = 672B).

Allocator routing is recorded in struct ntsync_q::from_cache (set in
ntsync_alloc_q, read in ntsync_free_q).  Field placed in the existing
2-byte trailing pad after `ownerdead`, so sizeof(struct ntsync_q) does
not change.

NULL-safety (1014a lesson)
==========================

kmem_cache_free is NOT NULL-safe under SLAB_FREELIST_HARDENED (per
mm/slub.c cache_from_obj derefing virt_to_cache(NULL) → vmemmap[0]+8
GP-fault — the exact crash 1014a fixed).  ntsync_free_q centralizes
the NULL guard with an early `if (!q) return;` so every call site is
trivially safe; no per-site `if (q)` audit needed.

PREEMPT_RT discipline (1006 alloc-hoist invariant)
==================================================

Both kmem_cache_alloc(..., GFP_KERNEL) and kmalloc(..., GFP_KERNEL) are
sleep-prone (they may direct-reclaim).  R1 from the ntsync-rt-audit
forbids sleeping operations under raw_spinlock_t.

Verified at every call site that ntsync_alloc_q runs at function entry,
before any obj_lock / wait_all_lock / boost_lock is acquired:

  setup_wait              line 2383 — top of function, no locks held
  ntsync_aggregate_setup  line 2829 — top of function, no locks held

And ntsync_free_q runs after every lock has been released and
ntsync_pi_work_finish has drained the boost-pool:

  setup_wait err          line 2421 — error cleanup, no locks held
  ntsync_wait_any         line 2573 — after unqueue + pi_work_finish
  ntsync_wait_all         line 2746 — after wait_all_lock unlock + pi_work_finish
  aggregate_setup err 1   line 2842 — fds alloc fail, no locks held
  aggregate_setup err 2   line 2891 — partial-init fail, no locks held
  ntsync_aggregate_wait   line 3083 — after unqueue + pi_work_finish

The 1006 alloc-hoist invariant is preserved end-to-end.

UAF / lifecycle (1012 lesson)
=============================

struct ntsync_q has a task-private lifecycle: it is allocated by the
syscalling task, populated by the same task, published into wait queues
under obj_lock, list_del'd under obj_lock during unqueue (mutually
exclusive with try_wake_any_*), and freed.  No cross-thread free path
exists.  The 1012 snapshot-vs-refcount lesson does not apply — there is
no lock-drop window between mutator and freer.

UAPI
====

struct ntsync_q is a kernel-private struct with no UAPI exposure.
Adding a `bool from_cache` field does not change any UAPI; ntsync.h is
unchanged.

Rollout
=======

Pattern matches 1013: add cache create/destroy to the existing
ntsync_init / ntsync_exit chain (mirrored unwind labels), ship as a
self-contained patch on top of post1014a.  Source-of-truth snapshot is
ntsync.c.post1015 (md5 in update-{prod,debug}-ntsync.sh after this
patch lands).

Validation
==========

Per-site audit (the 4-dimension audit established by 1014a):
  - NULL reachability: 1 alloc-fail return per site, all checked.
                       ntsync_free_q wraps the NULL guard centrally.
  - Allocator pairing: every ntsync_alloc_q paired with ntsync_free_q
                       on every exit path.  No mixed kmalloc/
                       kmem_cache_free or kmem_cache_alloc/kfree.
  - Lifecycle:         caches created before misc_register, destroyed
                       after misc_deregister, mirrored unwind labels.
                       wait_q cache destroyed first in exit order.
  - 1014 semantics:    independent — does not touch the lockless
                       SEND_PI scan path.

Observability:
  /proc/slabinfo will show `ntsync_wait_q` cache; expect ~1-N active
  objects matching live in-flight WAIT_* ioctls per process.
  kmalloc-128 / -256 / -512 should NOT show ntsync_q traffic (proves
  isolation, mirroring the 1013 evidence pattern).

